n the deaths of nearly 1,900 suspected traffickers . There is much concern over the drug . The drug 's popularity increased in the mid-1990s . It has made [LOC Thailand] the world 's number one consumer . Pierre-Arnaud chouvy and [PER Joel] meissonnier state in their book [ORG Yaa BAA] recently published by the [ORG Institute of Research] on contemporary [LOC Southeast Asia] that the psychotropic drugs is used across society for both work and pleasure . Construction workers , sailors , farmers and taxi drivers take the drug to help them through long working days . Students use it to get through exam periods . Clubbers use it to help them dance all night . [ORG Yaa BAA] possesses several qualities that have helped it supplant heroin as the drug of choice in [LOC Thailand] . The book states that the drug conveys a completely positive image . It appears modern and inoffensive because it is synthetic . The energy , confidence and euphoric feeling has given users an image as a drug of happiness . The pills can also be easily consumed . They can be popped or dissolved in a glass of water , taken intravenously , pulverized and inhaled , or smoked . There are at least 90 types of the pill . [ORG Yaa BAA] is easy to manufacture and do not have any climate uncertainties like other drugs have . Instructions on how to manufacture the drug are available on the [MISC Internet] . Heroin requires opium poppy as its raw ingredient and cocaine depends on yields from the coca plant . The drug has an affordable price . It cost 60 baht ( 1.50 dollars ) per pill on the streets before [LOC Thailand] 's drug war started on February 1 , 2003 and push the price up 300 percent . The pill costs five-cents to produce . 800 million pills entered [LOC Thailand] from [LOC Myanmar] last year . The book states that the majority of the drug comes from [LOC Myanmar] particularly the areas controlled by the [LOC Wa] of the [ORG UWSA] ( [ORG United Wa State Army] ) . The book is referring to the pro-Yangon ethnic group said to operate around 50 laboratories close to the border and the mobile production units . [LOC Myanmar] could become an unrivaled regional producer because of the links between the military rulers and the [ORG UWSA] , and the jungle canopy where [ORG UWSA] operate . The military and [ORG UWSA] links result in a lack of law enforcement . The drug has become a specialty of the [LOC Golden Triangle] where [LOC Thailand] , [LOC Laos] and [LOC Myanmar] converge . Much of the world 's opium is still produced there . Chouvy and meissonnier say that methamphetamine is overtaking heroin as the production drug of choice in the area and is profiting enormously from the distribution networks that heroin trafficking has already established . Five percent of [LOC Thailand] 's population is now estimated to abuse methamphetamine . The [ORG International Narcotics Control Bureau] says the figure makes it the largest per capita consumer in the world . The drug has been around in other forms for years . It was first used in the 1920s as an antidepressant and then as a psychostimulant during [MISC World War II] and the [ORG Vietnam War] . People recruited from impoverished ethnic minorities transport the pills along a multitude of routes . [LOC Myanmar] soldiers and [MISC Thai] police and bureaucrats protect the cargo and allow them to eventually reach consumers in [LOC Thailand] . The books states that one pill will pass through seven intermediaries from the frontier runner to the retailer . The retailer will usually sell more to the drug user than he or she requires . This creates another dealer and explains the drug 's easy availability across [LOC Thailand] . Owners of boats in the southern coastal province of [LOC Ranong] and construction foremen in [LOC Bangkok] are known to force their workers to take the drug at the beginning of the workday . Occasionally in rural areas the farmers dissolve the drug in a bottle which they drink while working . Consumers are as young as seven and school has become one of the main hubs for trafficking of methamphetamine . [LOC Thailand] 's youth are the most at risk . 2003-04-03 [LOC Afghanistan] ( AF ) ; [LOC Pakistan] ( [LOC PK] ) International ; terrorism ; Government ; war and conflict [LOC Afghanistan] 's Interior Minister states that [ORG Taliban] is not capable of destabilizing the [MISC Afghan] government despite post-winter increase in attacks on government and foreign targets in the country . Most of the attacks are carried out by [MISC Pakistan-based] former [ORG Taliban] members sent into [LOC Afghanistan] and funded by drug smuggling operations or supporters in [LOC Pakistan] . On 03 April 2003 [LOC Afghanistan] 's Interior Minister [PER Ali Ahmad Jalali] stated that [ORG Taliban] and remaining al-Qaeda militants are not capable of destabilizing the [MISC Afghan] government despite their increased attacks on government and foreign targets . [PER Jalali] was speaking at his first press conference since taking office in February 2003 . [PER Jalali] stated that the arrival of spring weather was the reason for the increased number of attacks by [ORG Taliban] and remaining members of [PER Osama bin Laden] 's al-Qaeda network . The traditional fighting season in [LOC Afghanistan] is spring after the harsh winters . [PER Jalali] stated that due to the warmer spring weather terrorist activities have increased particularly in the south and southeast regions of [LOC Afghanistan] . On 02 April 2003 the [ORG U.S. State Department] stated that security in [LOC Afghanistan] was volatile and unpredictable following a series of attacks against foreigners . In a travel advisory the [ORG U.S. State Department] stated that travel in all areas of [LOC Afghanistan] including the capital [LOC Kabul] is unsafe due to military operations , land mines , banditry , armed rivalry among political and tribal groups , and the possibility of terrorist attacks including attacks using vehicular or other bo